+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RwJ8z877XUzWMzo9vy9CEf","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- build, tests, and lint all pass. Now let me perform a thorough code review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Plugin Marketplace System\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nAll 64 tests pass, the build compiles cleanly, and lint produces no warnings. The implementation covers all five modules and the integration layer as required. The code is generally well-structured, readable, and conforms to the type interfaces. Below I detail the issues I found, categorized by severity.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. `installPlugin` resolves dependencies then throws -- logic ordering bug\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 58-81\n\nThe `installPlugin` function first filters constraints into \"resolvable\" (those with available versions) and \"missing\" groups on lines 70-76. It resolves the resolvable ones on line 72, and then on lines 76-81 it throws for missing ones. The problem is that **it resolves first, then throws**. This means the resolver does unnecessary work before the function always throws anyway. More importantly, the plugin has already been registered on line 52 (`registry.register(manifest)`) before the missing-dependency check. When the function throws on line 78, the plugin remains in the registry even though installation failed.\n\nThis is the inverse of the circular-dependency check on lines 84-89, which correctly removes the plugin from the registry before throwing.\n\n```typescript\n// Lines 52-81: Plugin is registered BEFORE dependency validation\nregistry.register(manifest);\n\n// ... later ...\nconst missing = constraints.filter(c => !available[c.name]);\nif (missing.length > 0) {\n  // BUG: Plugin stays registered even though install fails\n  throw new Error(\n    `Missing dependencies: ${missing.map(m => m.name).join(', ')}`\n  );\n}\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Either check for missing dependencies before registering, or add a `registry.remove()` call before throwing (matching the circular-dependency pattern). The cleanest fix is to check for missing dependencies before calling `registry.register()`:\n\n```typescript\nasync function installPlugin(manifest: PluginManifest): Promise<InstallResult> {\n  // ... validation ...\n\n  // Check for missing dependencies BEFORE registering\n  const depEntries = Object.entries(manifest.dependencies || {});\n  if (depEntries.length > 0) {\n    const available: Record<string, string[]> = {};\n    for (const [depName] of depEntries) {\n      const versions = registry.listVersions(depName);\n      if (versions.length > 0) {\n        available[depName] = versions;\n      }\n    }\n    const missing = depEntries.filter(([name]) => !available[name]);\n    if (missing.length > 0) {\n      throw new Error(\n        `Missing dependencies: ${missing.map(([name]) => name).join(', ')}`\n      );\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Now safe to register\n  registry.register(manifest);\n  // ... resolve, cycle check, execute ...\n}\n```\n\n**Impact:** Currently the test for missing dependencies still passes because the test does not check whether the plugin was left behind in the registry. However, any downstream code that queries the registry after a failed install would find a phantom entry that should not exist.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `detectCycles` DFS copies both `path` and `visited` on each branch -- false negatives possible\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 28-55\n\nThe `detectCycles` function creates copies of both `path` and `visited` when recursing into each dependency on line 46:\n\n```typescript\nfor (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n  dfs(depName, [...path], new Set(visited));\n}\n```\n\nCreating `new Set(visited)` for each branch means that nodes visited in one sibling branch are not seen when exploring another sibling branch. While this does not cause false positives (it will still find cycles that exist), it causes redundant traversal. More critically, the `path.pop()` on line 51 is dead code because `path` is already a copy at each recursive call and the pop modifies the local copy after all child calls are done. This works by accident -- the algorithm is correct but the code structure is misleading.\n\n**Impact:** Medium. The algorithm produces correct results for the test cases, but the dead `path.pop()` and the mixed copy-vs-mutate pattern indicates a half-refactored algorithm. If someone later switches back to a mutating approach (removing the `[...path]` copy) without also fixing the `new Set(visited)` copy, correctness would break.\n\n**Recommendation:** Choose one consistent style. For the copying approach, remove the dead `path.pop()`. Or better, use the standard mutating DFS pattern used in `topologicalSort`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(current: string, path: string[], visited: Set<string>, recStack: Set<string>): void {\n  if (recStack.has(current)) {\n    const cycleStart = path.indexOf(current);\n    cycles.push([...path.slice(cycleStart), current]);\n    return;\n  }\n  if (visited.has(current)) return;\n\n  visited.add(current);\n  recStack.add(current);\n  path.push(current);\n\n  const manifest = registry.get(current);\n  if (manifest) {\n    for (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n      dfs(depName, path, visited, recStack);\n    }\n  }\n\n  path.pop();\n  recStack.delete(current);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority Issues (Should Fix)\n\n### 3. `registry.get()` uses lexicographic ORDER BY, not semver ordering\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 26\n\n```typescript\nconst getLatestStmt = db.prepare(\n  `SELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ? ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1`\n);\n```\n\nThis sorts versions as strings. For semver, `\"9.0.0\"` sorts higher than `\"10.0.0\"` lexicographically because `'9' > '1'`. So if a plugin has versions `[\"1.0.0\", \"2.0.0\", \"10.0.0\"]`, the `get()` method would return version `\"9.0.0\"` if it existed, or `\"2.0.0\"` over `\"10.0.0\"`.\n\nThe `DepsService` relies on `registry.get()` to obtain the \"current\" manifest when building dependency trees, detecting cycles, etc. If the wrong version is returned, dependency analysis would operate on the wrong manifest.\n\n**Impact:** This will cause incorrect behavior for any plugin with version numbers where string sorting diverges from semver sorting (e.g., versions 2.x vs 10.x). The current tests do not exercise this because they only use single-digit major versions.\n\n**Recommendation:** Fetch all versions and use `semver.maxSatisfying` or `semver.sort` to find the true latest, or store a parsed sortable version column:\n\n```typescript\nget(name: string): PluginManifest | null {\n  const rows = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ?').all(name) as Record<string, unknown>[];\n  if (rows.length === 0) return null;\n  const manifests = rows.map(rowToManifest);\n  // Sort by semver descending\n  manifests.sort((a, b) => semver.rcompare(a.version, b.version));\n  return manifests[0];\n},\n```\n\n### 4. `resolver.test.ts` is missing the `beforeEach` import\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/resolver/resolver.test.ts`, line 1\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nThe file uses `beforeEach` on line 8 but does not import it from vitest. This works because vitest exposes globals by default in many configurations, but it is inconsistent with every other test file which explicitly imports `beforeEach`. If the vitest config ever disables globals, this test file would break while the others would not.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add `beforeEach` to the import:\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect, beforeEach } from 'vitest';\n```\n\n### 5. `createMarketplace` passes the same `dbPath` to both registry and reviews\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 33-36\n\n```typescript\nexport function createMarketplace(dbPath?: string): Marketplace {\n  const registry = createRegistry(dbPath);\n  // ...\n  const reviews = createReviewService(dbPath);\n```\n\nBoth services create their own `Database` instance pointing to the same file. If a non-`:memory:` path is provided, they will both try to create tables in the same SQLite file. Currently the table names do not collide (`plugins` vs `reviews`), so this works, but it creates two separate database connections to the same file, which can cause WAL-mode locking issues under concurrent access and is architecturally fragile.\n\nWhen `dbPath` is `undefined`, both default to `':memory:'`, but each gets its own independent in-memory database, which is the correct behavior for isolation. However, the implicit coupling here is worth documenting or resolving.\n\n**Impact:** Medium. Works for current usage patterns but could cause subtle issues with persistent storage.\n\n### 6. `runner.test.ts` is missing the `beforeEach` import (same as issue 4)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/runner/runner.test.ts`, line 1\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nUses `beforeEach` on line 8 but does not import it.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority Issues (Nice to Fix)\n\n### 7. `buildTree` uses `new Set(visited)` creating a shallow copy per branch -- exponential traversal on deep diamond graphs\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, line 18\n\n```typescript\ndepNodes.push(buildTree(depName, registry, new Set(visited)));\n```\n\nEach sibling dependency gets its own copy of the visited set. In a diamond dependency graph (A depends on B and C, both depend on D), node D would be visited twice. For deeper diamond patterns this becomes exponential. This is the same copy-per-branch pattern as `detectCycles`.\n\n**Recommendation:** For `buildTree` specifically, the copy-per-branch approach is intentional to allow the same dependency to appear in multiple subtrees (which is correct for tree representation). However, consider documenting this design choice with a comment to avoid future confusion.\n\n### 8. No input validation for review ratings at the application layer\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts`\n\nThe SQL schema enforces `CHECK(rating >= 1 AND rating <= 5)` on line 13, but there is no application-level validation. If someone passes `rating: 0` or `rating: 6`, the error would be an opaque SQLite constraint violation rather than a clear application error message.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add validation in `addReview`:\n\n```typescript\naddReview(review: Omit<Review, 'id' | 'createdAt' | 'flagged'>): Review {\n  if (review.rating < 1 || review.rating > 5 || !Number.isInteger(review.rating)) {\n    throw new Error('Rating must be an integer between 1 and 5');\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n### 9. `registry.get()` description says \"get latest\" but the `DepsService` treats it as \"get the plugin\"\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 5-8 and `/workspace/src/types.ts`, line 51\n\nThe `RegistryService.get()` type signature is `get(name: string): PluginManifest | null` -- it does not specify which version it returns. The implementation returns whatever SQLite's lexicographic `ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1` picks. The `DepsService` calls `registry.get(name)` to get a plugin's dependency list, but it has no way to ask for a specific version. This means dependency analysis always uses one arbitrary version's dependency list, even if multiple versions exist with different dependencies.\n\n**Impact:** This is an architectural limitation. If plugin `foo@1.0.0` has no dependencies but `foo@2.0.0` depends on `bar`, the dependency tree for `foo` would be built from whichever version `get()` returns, which may not be the version actually being installed.\n\n### 10. SQL injection via search query is mitigated but LIKE wildcards are not escaped\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 93\n\n```typescript\nconst pattern = `%${query}%`;\n```\n\nWhile SQL injection is prevented by using parameterized queries, if a user searches for `%` or `_`, these are LIKE wildcards and would match more broadly than intended. For example, searching for `%` would match every plugin.\n\n**Recommendation:** Escape LIKE special characters:\n\n```typescript\nconst escaped = query.replace(/[%_]/g, '\\\\$&');\nconst pattern = `%${escaped}%`;\n```\nAnd update the query to use `ESCAPE '\\\\'`.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Priority | Issue | File | Impact |\n|----------|-------|------|--------|\n| CRITICAL | Plugin stays registered after missing-dependency failure | `/workspace/src/index.ts:52-81` | Ghost entries in registry after failed installs |\n| CRITICAL | `detectCycles` has dead code (`path.pop()`) and mixed mutation/copy pattern | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:28-55` | Misleading code, maintenance hazard |\n| HIGH | `registry.get()` uses lexicographic sort, not semver | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts:26` | Wrong \"latest\" version for multi-digit majors |\n| HIGH | Missing `beforeEach` import in resolver and runner tests | `/workspace/src/resolver/resolver.test.ts:1`, `/workspace/src/runner/runner.test.ts:1` | Fragile test setup relying on implicit globals |\n| HIGH | Same dbPath used for registry and reviews databases | `/workspace/src/index.ts:33-36` | Potential locking issues with persistent storage |\n| MEDIUM | `buildTree` exponential traversal on diamond graphs | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:18` | Performance on complex dependency graphs |\n| MEDIUM | No app-level validation for review ratings | `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts:67` | Opaque SQLite errors for invalid ratings |\n| MEDIUM | `DepsService` always uses one version's deps for analysis | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:5-8` | Incorrect analysis when multiple versions exist |\n| MEDIUM | LIKE wildcards not escaped in search | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts:93` | Overly broad search results |\n\n## What Was Done Well\n\n- Clean separation of concerns across five modules plus integration layer, matching the task requirements exactly.\n- Proper use of prepared statements throughout both SQLite-backed modules, preventing SQL injection.\n- Thorough test coverage (64 tests) with good edge case coverage for each module.\n- Correct JSON serialization/deserialization for `dependencies` and `permissions` fields in the registry.\n- The `rowToReview` function correctly converts the SQLite integer `flagged` column to a boolean.\n- The runner properly handles VM context errors that may not be `instanceof Error`.\n- The topological sort algorithm is correctly implemented with the standard visiting/visited dual-set pattern.\n- The integration layer correctly cleans up (removes the plugin from registry) when a circular dependency is detected."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a6a08d7 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 38186\ntool_uses: 20\nduration_ms: 101964</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c9797534-91fa-4c5d-889f-7e2b43d26c4c","uuid":"6d84f628-c1c2-4ed7-84de-9b94b7a4a44f","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of the plugin marketplace system. The task was to build 5 modules (registry, resolver, runner, reviews, deps) plus an integration layer. Check for:\n\n1. Correctness issues - edge cases, logic bugs\n2. Code quality issues - dead code, debug artifacts\n3. Missing functionality relative to the requirements\n4. Type safety issues\n\nThe implementation files are:\n- src/registry/index.ts - Plugin registry using better-sqlite3\n- src/resolver/index.ts - Version resolver using semver\n- src/runner/index.ts - Sandboxed runner using vm module\n- src/reviews/index.ts - Review system using better-sqlite3\n- src/deps/index.ts - Dependency graph analysis\n- src/index.ts - Integration layer with createMarketplace and installPlugin\n\nThe types are in src/types.ts (read-only).\n\nFocus on HIGH and MEDIUM priority issues that could cause test failures or incorrect behavior.","agentId":"a6a08d7","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- build, tests, and lint all pass. Now let me perform a thorough code review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Plugin Marketplace System\n\n## Overall Assessment\n\nAll 64 tests pass, the build compiles cleanly, and lint produces no warnings. The implementation covers all five modules and the integration layer as required. The code is generally well-structured, readable, and conforms to the type interfaces. Below I detail the issues I found, categorized by severity.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. `installPlugin` resolves dependencies then throws -- logic ordering bug\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 58-81\n\nThe `installPlugin` function first filters constraints into \"resolvable\" (those with available versions) and \"missing\" groups on lines 70-76. It resolves the resolvable ones on line 72, and then on lines 76-81 it throws for missing ones. The problem is that **it resolves first, then throws**. This means the resolver does unnecessary work before the function always throws anyway. More importantly, the plugin has already been registered on line 52 (`registry.register(manifest)`) before the missing-dependency check. When the function throws on line 78, the plugin remains in the registry even though installation failed.\n\nThis is the inverse of the circular-dependency check on lines 84-89, which correctly removes the plugin from the registry before throwing.\n\n```typescript\n// Lines 52-81: Plugin is registered BEFORE dependency validation\nregistry.register(manifest);\n\n// ... later ...\nconst missing = constraints.filter(c => !available[c.name]);\nif (missing.length > 0) {\n  // BUG: Plugin stays registered even though install fails\n  throw new Error(\n    `Missing dependencies: ${missing.map(m => m.name).join(', ')}`\n  );\n}\n```\n\n**Recommendation:** Either check for missing dependencies before registering, or add a `registry.remove()` call before throwing (matching the circular-dependency pattern). The cleanest fix is to check for missing dependencies before calling `registry.register()`:\n\n```typescript\nasync function installPlugin(manifest: PluginManifest): Promise<InstallResult> {\n  // ... validation ...\n\n  // Check for missing dependencies BEFORE registering\n  const depEntries = Object.entries(manifest.dependencies || {});\n  if (depEntries.length > 0) {\n    const available: Record<string, string[]> = {};\n    for (const [depName] of depEntries) {\n      const versions = registry.listVersions(depName);\n      if (versions.length > 0) {\n        available[depName] = versions;\n      }\n    }\n    const missing = depEntries.filter(([name]) => !available[name]);\n    if (missing.length > 0) {\n      throw new Error(\n        `Missing dependencies: ${missing.map(([name]) => name).join(', ')}`\n      );\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Now safe to register\n  registry.register(manifest);\n  // ... resolve, cycle check, execute ...\n}\n```\n\n**Impact:** Currently the test for missing dependencies still passes because the test does not check whether the plugin was left behind in the registry. However, any downstream code that queries the registry after a failed install would find a phantom entry that should not exist.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `detectCycles` DFS copies both `path` and `visited` on each branch -- false negatives possible\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 28-55\n\nThe `detectCycles` function creates copies of both `path` and `visited` when recursing into each dependency on line 46:\n\n```typescript\nfor (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n  dfs(depName, [...path], new Set(visited));\n}\n```\n\nCreating `new Set(visited)` for each branch means that nodes visited in one sibling branch are not seen when exploring another sibling branch. While this does not cause false positives (it will still find cycles that exist), it causes redundant traversal. More critically, the `path.pop()` on line 51 is dead code because `path` is already a copy at each recursive call and the pop modifies the local copy after all child calls are done. This works by accident -- the algorithm is correct but the code structure is misleading.\n\n**Impact:** Medium. The algorithm produces correct results for the test cases, but the dead `path.pop()` and the mixed copy-vs-mutate pattern indicates a half-refactored algorithm. If someone later switches back to a mutating approach (removing the `[...path]` copy) without also fixing the `new Set(visited)` copy, correctness would break.\n\n**Recommendation:** Choose one consistent style. For the copying approach, remove the dead `path.pop()`. Or better, use the standard mutating DFS pattern used in `topologicalSort`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction dfs(current: string, path: string[], visited: Set<string>, recStack: Set<string>): void {\n  if (recStack.has(current)) {\n    const cycleStart = path.indexOf(current);\n    cycles.push([...path.slice(cycleStart), current]);\n    return;\n  }\n  if (visited.has(current)) return;\n\n  visited.add(current);\n  recStack.add(current);\n  path.push(current);\n\n  const manifest = registry.get(current);\n  if (manifest) {\n    for (const depName of Object.keys(manifest.dependencies)) {\n      dfs(depName, path, visited, recStack);\n    }\n  }\n\n  path.pop();\n  recStack.delete(current);\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority Issues (Should Fix)\n\n### 3. `registry.get()` uses lexicographic ORDER BY, not semver ordering\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 26\n\n```typescript\nconst getLatestStmt = db.prepare(\n  `SELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ? ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1`\n);\n```\n\nThis sorts versions as strings. For semver, `\"9.0.0\"` sorts higher than `\"10.0.0\"` lexicographically because `'9' > '1'`. So if a plugin has versions `[\"1.0.0\", \"2.0.0\", \"10.0.0\"]`, the `get()` method would return version `\"9.0.0\"` if it existed, or `\"2.0.0\"` over `\"10.0.0\"`.\n\nThe `DepsService` relies on `registry.get()` to obtain the \"current\" manifest when building dependency trees, detecting cycles, etc. If the wrong version is returned, dependency analysis would operate on the wrong manifest.\n\n**Impact:** This will cause incorrect behavior for any plugin with version numbers where string sorting diverges from semver sorting (e.g., versions 2.x vs 10.x). The current tests do not exercise this because they only use single-digit major versions.\n\n**Recommendation:** Fetch all versions and use `semver.maxSatisfying` or `semver.sort` to find the true latest, or store a parsed sortable version column:\n\n```typescript\nget(name: string): PluginManifest | null {\n  const rows = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM plugins WHERE name = ?').all(name) as Record<string, unknown>[];\n  if (rows.length === 0) return null;\n  const manifests = rows.map(rowToManifest);\n  // Sort by semver descending\n  manifests.sort((a, b) => semver.rcompare(a.version, b.version));\n  return manifests[0];\n},\n```\n\n### 4. `resolver.test.ts` is missing the `beforeEach` import\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/resolver/resolver.test.ts`, line 1\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nThe file uses `beforeEach` on line 8 but does not import it from vitest. This works because vitest exposes globals by default in many configurations, but it is inconsistent with every other test file which explicitly imports `beforeEach`. If the vitest config ever disables globals, this test file would break while the others would not.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add `beforeEach` to the import:\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect, beforeEach } from 'vitest';\n```\n\n### 5. `createMarketplace` passes the same `dbPath` to both registry and reviews\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 33-36\n\n```typescript\nexport function createMarketplace(dbPath?: string): Marketplace {\n  const registry = createRegistry(dbPath);\n  // ...\n  const reviews = createReviewService(dbPath);\n```\n\nBoth services create their own `Database` instance pointing to the same file. If a non-`:memory:` path is provided, they will both try to create tables in the same SQLite file. Currently the table names do not collide (`plugins` vs `reviews`), so this works, but it creates two separate database connections to the same file, which can cause WAL-mode locking issues under concurrent access and is architecturally fragile.\n\nWhen `dbPath` is `undefined`, both default to `':memory:'`, but each gets its own independent in-memory database, which is the correct behavior for isolation. However, the implicit coupling here is worth documenting or resolving.\n\n**Impact:** Medium. Works for current usage patterns but could cause subtle issues with persistent storage.\n\n### 6. `runner.test.ts` is missing the `beforeEach` import (same as issue 4)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/runner/runner.test.ts`, line 1\n\n```typescript\nimport { describe, it, expect } from 'vitest';\n```\n\nUses `beforeEach` on line 8 but does not import it.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority Issues (Nice to Fix)\n\n### 7. `buildTree` uses `new Set(visited)` creating a shallow copy per branch -- exponential traversal on deep diamond graphs\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, line 18\n\n```typescript\ndepNodes.push(buildTree(depName, registry, new Set(visited)));\n```\n\nEach sibling dependency gets its own copy of the visited set. In a diamond dependency graph (A depends on B and C, both depend on D), node D would be visited twice. For deeper diamond patterns this becomes exponential. This is the same copy-per-branch pattern as `detectCycles`.\n\n**Recommendation:** For `buildTree` specifically, the copy-per-branch approach is intentional to allow the same dependency to appear in multiple subtrees (which is correct for tree representation). However, consider documenting this design choice with a comment to avoid future confusion.\n\n### 8. No input validation for review ratings at the application layer\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts`\n\nThe SQL schema enforces `CHECK(rating >= 1 AND rating <= 5)` on line 13, but there is no application-level validation. If someone passes `rating: 0` or `rating: 6`, the error would be an opaque SQLite constraint violation rather than a clear application error message.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add validation in `addReview`:\n\n```typescript\naddReview(review: Omit<Review, 'id' | 'createdAt' | 'flagged'>): Review {\n  if (review.rating < 1 || review.rating > 5 || !Number.isInteger(review.rating)) {\n    throw new Error('Rating must be an integer between 1 and 5');\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n### 9. `registry.get()` description says \"get latest\" but the `DepsService` treats it as \"get the plugin\"\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 5-8 and `/workspace/src/types.ts`, line 51\n\nThe `RegistryService.get()` type signature is `get(name: string): PluginManifest | null` -- it does not specify which version it returns. The implementation returns whatever SQLite's lexicographic `ORDER BY version DESC LIMIT 1` picks. The `DepsService` calls `registry.get(name)` to get a plugin's dependency list, but it has no way to ask for a specific version. This means dependency analysis always uses one arbitrary version's dependency list, even if multiple versions exist with different dependencies.\n\n**Impact:** This is an architectural limitation. If plugin `foo@1.0.0` has no dependencies but `foo@2.0.0` depends on `bar`, the dependency tree for `foo` would be built from whichever version `get()` returns, which may not be the version actually being installed.\n\n### 10. SQL injection via search query is mitigated but LIKE wildcards are not escaped\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts`, line 93\n\n```typescript\nconst pattern = `%${query}%`;\n```\n\nWhile SQL injection is prevented by using parameterized queries, if a user searches for `%` or `_`, these are LIKE wildcards and would match more broadly than intended. For example, searching for `%` would match every plugin.\n\n**Recommendation:** Escape LIKE special characters:\n\n```typescript\nconst escaped = query.replace(/[%_]/g, '\\\\$&');\nconst pattern = `%${escaped}%`;\n```\nAnd update the query to use `ESCAPE '\\\\'`.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| Priority | Issue | File | Impact |\n|----------|-------|------|--------|\n| CRITICAL | Plugin stays registered after missing-dependency failure | `/workspace/src/index.ts:52-81` | Ghost entries in registry after failed installs |\n| CRITICAL | `detectCycles` has dead code (`path.pop()`) and mixed mutation/copy pattern | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:28-55` | Misleading code, maintenance hazard |\n| HIGH | `registry.get()` uses lexicographic sort, not semver | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts:26` | Wrong \"latest\" version for multi-digit majors |\n| HIGH | Missing `beforeEach` import in resolver and runner tests | `/workspace/src/resolver/resolver.test.ts:1`, `/workspace/src/runner/runner.test.ts:1` | Fragile test setup relying on implicit globals |\n| HIGH | Same dbPath used for registry and reviews databases | `/workspace/src/index.ts:33-36` | Potential locking issues with persistent storage |\n| MEDIUM | `buildTree` exponential traversal on diamond graphs | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:18` | Performance on complex dependency graphs |\n| MEDIUM | No app-level validation for review ratings | `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts:67` | Opaque SQLite errors for invalid ratings |\n| MEDIUM | `DepsService` always uses one version's deps for analysis | `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts:5-8` | Incorrect analysis when multiple versions exist |\n| MEDIUM | LIKE wildcards not escaped in search | `/workspace/src/registry/index.ts:93` | Overly broad search results |\n\n## What Was Done Well\n\n- Clean separation of concerns across five modules plus integration layer, matching the task requirements exactly.\n- Proper use of prepared statements throughout both SQLite-backed modules, preventing SQL injection.\n- Thorough test coverage (64 tests) with good edge case coverage for each module.\n- Correct JSON serialization/deserialization for `dependencies` and `permissions` fields in the registry.\n- The `rowToReview` function correctly converts the SQLite integer `flagged` column to a boolean.\n- The runner properly handles VM context errors that may not be `instanceof Error`.\n- The topological sort algorithm is correctly implemented with the standard visiting/visited dual-set pattern.\n- The integration layer correctly cleans up (removes the plugin from registry) when a circular dependency is detected."}],"totalDurationMs":101964,"totalTokens":38186,"totalToolUseCount":20,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":212,"cache_read_input_tokens":34221,"output_tokens":3752,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":212,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[]}}}
